    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 18th with a clear focal point in **Yordan Alvarez**, who anchors the roster with an elite 77.33 efficiency score. Facing Andre Pallante, **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a strong platoon advantage and a favorable SP skill matchup, positioning him as the primary engine for our power categories. We also see significant value in **Hyeseong Kim** (70.16) and **Colt Keith** (68.51). **Hyeseong Kim** remains a priority start despite a low batting order position; his matchup against Ryan Feltner is bolstered by a high park factor and a tactical edge against a slow-delivery pitcher that maximizes his stolen base potential. Similarly, **Colt Keith** is locked in as a high-floor play, with his placement in the heart of the order and a clear platoon advantage against Bello making him one of our most reliable assets today.\n\nOur most difficult personnel decision involved **Caleb Durbin**, who ultimately ended up on the bench with a 42.48 score. While **Caleb Durbin** is a coveted source of stolen bases, his matchup against an elite arm like Skubal effectively neutralized his upside, forcing him below the threshold required to displace our starters. Caution is advised regarding the top of our lineup: **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber** are both set to face Chris Sale. While **Kyle Schwarber** maintains a strong 0.402 xwOBA, the elite 2.88 xERA of the opposing pitcher creates a non-trivial risk of stagnation. Furthermore, with lineup status still \"pending\" for several players, including **Gary Sanchez**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Trea Turner**, **Kyle Schwarber**, **Yordan Alvarez**, and **Victor Scott II**, we must remain vigilant for mid-day scratch updates. **Victor Scott II** is a high-variance play at 59.37; his speed is a vital component of our strategy, but his #9 spot and the presence of Lance McCullers Jr. mean his value is highly dependent on his ability to get on base for the top of the order.",
